Purpose: Append AWS Implementation - Why These Services and Architecture Diagram

[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The recruitment conversationalist maps to a familiar AWS service set. The selection follows the same logic as the previous chapter 11 recipes, with the recruitment-specific extensions (IRB-approved-content corpus, eligibility-evaluation engine, trial-state tracker, coordinator-handoff orchestration, per-cohort representativeness monitoring) layered on the shared backbone.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Bedrock with Anthropic Claude** is the conversation engine. The Bedrock Agents pattern from recipes 11.2 through 11.9 is the right level of abstraction: the agent handles the multi-step LLM-and-tool orchestration, the action groups expose the recruitment tools (FAQ retrieval, eligibility-evaluation, prescreen-data-capture, handoff scheduling, trial-state lookup), and the model is anchored by the per-trial system prompt with strict citation grounding instructions. The recruitment posture is deliberately conservative; Claude's tendency toward conservative completion in regulated contexts is an asset.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Bedrock Knowledge Bases** is the IRB-approved-content corpus. Each trial has a per-trial knowledge base populated from the IRB-approved trial summary, eligibility criteria, FAQ entries, visit-schedule summary, study-procedure summary, and IRB-and-protocol identifiers. The knowledge base is content-isolated per trial (so a conversation about Trial A cannot retrieve content from Trial B), with version-stamped sources and IRB-approval metadata on each source. The retrieval is configured for strict citation grounding: the assistant cannot deliver trial-specific content that did not come back as a retrieved citation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Bedrock Guardrails** layers safety filtering with recruitment-specific denied topics: medical-advice solicitation, recommendations on whether to enroll, comparisons among trials, protocol-confidential disclosure, and attempts to bypass eligibility-evaluation. The guardrail configuration is per-trial-aware; a trial that opens enrollment requires a different guardrail profile than a trial in pediatric oncology.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon OpenSearch Serverless** backs the vector index for the IRB-approved-content corpus and the per-trial FAQ corpus. The indexing pipeline embeds each IRB-approved passage with the embedding model, stamps the IRB-approved-version metadata, and writes the vector. Retrieval combines the vector search with lexical (BM25) search for robustness on clinical terminology that does not embed well.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Lambda** runs the action-group implementations: the FAQ retrieval tool (retrieves and reranks IRB-approved FAQ entries), the eligibility-evaluation tool (deterministic per-criterion logic with named clinical-leadership ownership), the prescreen-data-capture tool (writes prescreen artifacts to the research-data store), the handoff-scheduling tool (creates the structured handoff packet and posts to the coordinator queue), the trial-state-lookup tool (reads the current trial-state and amendment status), and the emergency-pathway-routing tool (interrupts the recruitment conversation for safety events). Each Lambda runs under least-privilege IAM and validates patient-and-session context against the verified session token to defend against prompt-injection-driven argument spoofing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Step Functions** orchestrates the multi-step recruitment workflows that span beyond a single Bedrock Agents turn: trial-onboarding-and-publishing, IRB-amendment-rollout, in-flight-conversation-amendment-transition, post-conversation handoff fan-out, and reconciliation jobs against the coordinator-team workflow tooling. Each workflow is a deterministic, observable, retryable state machine.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon API Gateway with AWS WAF** is the recruitment-platform front door. WAF applies bot-defense, rate-limiting, geo-screening (where applicable), and request-validation rules. API Gateway terminates TLS, applies the per-channel authentication, and routes to the conversation-runtime Lambda. Per-channel session-token TTLs and per-channel access-control scopes are enforced at this layer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB** is the operational state store: conversation state, prescreen artifacts (with patient-reported tags), handoff packets, trial-state cache, per-conversation audit headers, and per-cohort funnel-counter state. DynamoDB's single-digit-millisecond latency and per-item TTL make it the right fit for the high-volume, low-latency operational state.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon S3 with Object Lock** is the IRB-grade record store: full conversation transcripts, prescreen-artifact documents, handoff packets at handoff time, coordinator-disposition records, and the IRB-approved-content versions in effect during the conversation. Object Lock with compliance-mode retention enforces the institutional research-data-retention policy. KMS-customer-managed-keys (CMKs) encrypt at rest with research-data-specific key policies.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS HealthLake** stores the patient's longitudinal clinical context where consent permits and where the trial's eligibility prescreen benefits from chart context (recent labs, current medication list, recent diagnoses). HealthLake's FHIR-native model is the right shape for the chart-context retrieval. The recruitment-conversation access to HealthLake is consent-gated per the IRB-approved data-access plan.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon EventBridge** is the recruitment-lifecycle event bus: conversation-started, disclosure-acknowledged, prescreen-started, prescreen-completed, handoff-initiated, handoff-accepted, coordinator-disposition-recorded, trial-state-changed, amendment-published, recruitment-paused, recruitment-resumed, recruitment-closed. Downstream consumers include the analytics pipeline, the coordinator-workflow integration, the IRB-reporting pipeline, and the diversity-action-plan reporting pipeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose** streams the conversation event log, the per-cohort funnel-counter state, the eligibility-evaluation tool calls and outcomes, and the per-conversation audit headers to S3 for downstream analytics. The firehose-to-S3 path enforces format normalization and partitioning by trial, by date, and by channel.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Glue with Amazon Athena** runs the per-cohort recruitment-funnel analytics, the per-trial recruitment-equity dashboards, and the diversity-action-plan reporting queries. The analytics layer is research-data-grade with audit logging and access controls separate from the clinical-care analytics layer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon QuickSight** renders the per-cohort recruitment-funnel dashboards, the per-trial diversity-action-plan reports, the operational-handoff-aging dashboards, and the equity-monitoring dashboards. Dashboard access is role-based: principal investigator, recruitment operations, sponsor's recruitment team, IRB liaison, and (for sponsor-funded trials) sponsor diversity-action-plan team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Pinpoint** delivers SMS recruitment messaging (entry confirmations, handoff confirmations, follow-up reminders) where the patient has opted in to SMS engagement per the trial's IRB-approved SMS-consent posture. TCPA-compliant SMS with 10DLC-registered messaging is the production posture. Email channel integration for asynchronous patient engagement is supported via Pinpoint or via SES depending on institutional preference.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Connect** provides the voice-channel surface for patients who prefer voice, patients with disabilities affecting written communication, and patients without smartphones. The Connect contact flow integrates the same recruitment-conversation backbone with voice-specific cadence: slower pacing, briefer responses, voice-friendly disclosure language, and accessibility-aware design. Crisis-pathway integrity is preserved across channels.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SageMaker** is the optional home for institution-trained models that augment the recruitment conversation: a custom embedding model fine-tuned for clinical-terminology robustness, a per-cohort eligibility-likelihood prior model that helps prioritize handoff routing within coordinator capacity, and a representativeness-monitoring model that flags emerging cohort-disparities. SageMaker is not required for the baseline deployment; it is the natural home if the institution invests in model-development beyond the Bedrock-managed models.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Secrets Manager** holds integration credentials: the coordinator-workflow tool credentials, the trial-data-management-system credentials, the sponsor-portal credentials, the EHR research-flag credentials. Secrets rotation is on the standard institutional schedule.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS CloudTrail** logs all API activity for IRB-grade audit. The CloudTrail logs are the lower-level audit; the conversation-level audit log on top of it captures the operational and clinical decision context.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Identity and Access Management** with attribute-based access control governs operational access. The per-trial access scopes are the dominant access dimension; the institutional research-recruitment team has cross-trial access; the per-trial coordinator teams have per-trial access; the principal investigators have access to their trials; sponsor-recruitment teams have read-only access to their sponsored trials per BAA.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The Bedrock Agents pattern is, again, doing the heavy LLM-and-tool-orchestration work. The institutional value lives in the IRB-approved-content corpus, the eligibility-evaluation engine, the coordinator-workflow integration, the trial-state tracker, the per-cohort representativeness monitoring, and the regulatory artifact, not in the Bedrock features themselves.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart TB
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Patient[Prospective Participant]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Caregiver[Caregiver / Surrogate]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ClinicianRef[Referring Clinician<br/>EHR e-Referral]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     SponsorAd[Sponsor Recruitment<br/>Channel / Registry]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Channels[Channel Surface]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Web[Web Chat Widget]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         App[In-App Chat]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         SMS[SMS via Pinpoint]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Voice[Voice via Connect]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph FrontDoor[Front Door]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         WAF[AWS WAF]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         APIGW[Amazon API Gateway]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Auth[Patient Identity<br/>+ Role Resolver]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph ConversationRuntime[Conversation Runtime]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Agent[Amazon Bedrock Agent<br/>Claude on Bedrock]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Guardrails[Bedrock Guardrails<br/>Recruitment Profile]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         SystemPrompt[Per-Trial System Prompt<br/>+ IRB Disclosures]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph TrialContext[Trial Context Layer]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         TrialState[Trial State Service<br/>DynamoDB]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         AmendTrack[Amendment Tracker]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ContentCorpus[IRB-Approved Content<br/>Bedrock Knowledge Bases]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FAQVector[FAQ Vector Index<br/>OpenSearch Serverless]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph ActionGroups[Bedrock Agent Action Groups]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FAQTool[FAQ Retrieval Lambda]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         EligTool[Eligibility Evaluation Lambda]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         PrescreenTool[Prescreen Capture Lambda]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         HandoffTool[Handoff Scheduling Lambda]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         TrialLookup[Trial State Lookup Lambda]
